solution.p:
On the other hand, we earlier solved for y as an explicit function y=-\frac{3}{2}x+3. Substituting x=2 into this equation directly gives us the desired value. 
                    y&=-{\textstyle \frac{2}{3}}x+2
                    y&=-{\textstyle \frac{2}{3}}(2)+2 =-{\textstyle \frac{4}{3}}+{\textstyle \frac{6}{3}}={\textstyle \frac{2}{3}}

li.p:
For the first data set, we measure the slope if we compare the first point with each of the other two points. If those are the same, then the data are consistent with a linear relation. Let us label the states (x_1,y_1)=(1,5), (x_2,y_2)=(4,3), and (x_3,y_3)=(10,-1). Compute the slopes: 
                             \frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1} &= \frac{3-5}{4-1} = -\frac{2}{3} 
                             \frac{y_3-y_1}{x_3-x_1} &= \frac{-1-5}{10-1} = -\frac{6}{9} = -\frac{2}{3} 
                         Because the slopes are the same value m=-\frac{2}{3}, there is a linear relation with these states.

To simplify f(4), we see that the value inside parentheses is 4. So we substitute the independent variable with the value 4. 
                            f(x) &= -{\textstyle \frac{2}{3}}x+2
                            f(4) &= -{\textstyle \frac{2}{3}}(4)+2 = {-\textstyle \frac{8}{3} + \frac{6}{3}} = {\textstyle -\frac{2}{3}}
